[2] Norovirus, hospitals - New Zealand
Date: Wed 1 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Stuff.co.nz, New Zealand, 1 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/0,2106,3017952a7144,00.html>

New Zealand: Country-wide Norovirus Outbreaks Affect Hospitals and Rest Homes
-------------------------------------------------
Highly contagious gastroenteritis viruses, known as noroviruses, have
paralysed hospitals and caused havoc in rest homes throughout New Zealand
this winter, with more than double the usual number of cases. An
Environmental Science and Research report showed there were about 35
reported norovirus outbreaks in the quarter to 30 Jun 2004, resulting in
890 cases of illness. This was a huge jump from the 2003 figures, when 102
reported outbreaks caused 348 cases. The disease causes diarrhoea and
vomiting and usually lasts about 24 hours. It is not usually serious, but
can be dangerous for children and the elderly. It can be spread by infected
shellfish, poor food handling hygiene or person-to-person.
The virus closed wards at Wellington, Kenepuru, Horowhenua, Wairau
(Blenheim) and Princess Margaret (Christchurch) hospitals. In Wellington,
at least 424 people were infected, including 208 Wellington and Kenepuru
hospital patients and staff. In 2003, there were just 8 outbreaks
investigated in the greater Wellington area, which caused 214 cases.
Wellington Medical Officer of Health, Margot McLean, said norovirus
outbreaks had been more prevalent and had a much bigger impact this year.
The figures were just the tip of the iceberg. Though outbreaks in rest
homes and hospitals were usually reported, outbreaks in the community were
not. Most of the Wellington outbreaks happened in May and June, but cases
in rest homes continued into July, she said.
ESR communicable diseases scientist Gail Greening said norovirus rates were
high worldwide. 2004's outbreaks were caused by 2 main strains, one of
which appeared to be the same as the strain circulating on cruise ships in
America. Though there had been fewer outbreaks this year, the "attack rate"
had been high, with more people becoming infected, Dr Greening said. The
latest strains seemed to be more aggressive, causing a higher number of
cases. The outbreaks had had significant economic impact, especially for
hospitals, she said.
[Byline: Nikki Macdonald]
