[3] Gastroenteritis, cruise ship - United Kingdom (Scotland)
Date: Wed 1 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Press and Journal, Wed 1 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://www.thisisnorthscotland.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=149475&command=displayContent&sourceNode=149205&contentPK=10868607>

United Kingdom: : Cruise Ship (ex Germany) Quarantined in Scottish Port
------------------------------------------------
A Cruise ship was quarantined after passengers were taken ill on Tue 31 Aug
2004. Dozens of holidaymakers on the German-owned Mona Lisa complained of
feeling unwell as the vessel was en route to Peterhead. No one was allowed
to board or leave the ship when she arrived in the Buchan port yesterday
morning. After an investigation by health chiefs and environmental officers
into the outbreak of sickness and diarrhoea, planned day trips ashore were
given the go-ahead.
The majority of the 700-plus passengers on the 660-ft ship were German. The
vessel had called at Rosyth before sailing for the north-east and was
heading for Orkney today before moving on to Dublin as part of a cruise
around Britain and Ireland. The Mona Lisa, which also had some 300 crew on
board, arrived in Peterhead about 7am.
By late morning, the captain was told that anyone who felt well enough to
go ashore was free to do so. An NHS Grampian spokeswoman said: "Our own
health-protection team and Aberdeenshire Council environmental-health
officers are investigating an outbreak of diarrhoea and vomiting amongst
passengers and crew of the cruise ship. 67 people have reported symptoms,
and the illness appears to be short-lived. Measures have been put in place
to limit the spread of infection among the other passengers and crew. All
the passengers on board the ship have been advised of the situation."
The visit of the Mona Lisa -- which had been due to call at Peterhead
during the summer of 2003 until she ran aground in Norway -- marked the end
of the port's most successful cruise season since it launched itself as a
destination for cruise ships in 1997. The 38-year-old Mona Lisa was built
in the UK and spent most of her life working as the Victoria for P&O Cruises.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Norovirus infection has been a frequent cause of illness on cruise ships
world-wide. The relaxed attitude of the local medical authorities suggests
that the outbreak has passed its peak and that symptomless passengers are
free of infection and not a hazard to the local community. - Mod.CP]
