[4] Unresolved multiple cause outbreak, vacation resort - USA (Ohio)
Date: Fri 27 Aug 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

USA: Outbreak of Gastroenteritis at Put-in-Bay Vacation Resort in Ohio
---------------------------------------------------
In ProMED-mail post "Viral gastroenteritis update 2004 (27) 20040818.2284"
it was reported that in recent weeks a mystery sickness has afflicted
Put-in-Bay residents, summer workers and visitors. Symptoms include nausea,
vomiting, fever, headache, abdominal cramps and diarrhea, typically lasting
up to 24 hours or so. The Ohio Department of Health classified the
incidents as an outbreak of gastrointestinal illness. Laboratory analysis
was being performed on stool and vomit samples from stricken victims. As of
21 Aug 2004, the source of the illness and methods of transmission had not
been identified, but results were expected later in the week.
The etiology of this outbreak is obscure, and further investigation of the
outbreak can be followed in the ProMED thread entitled "Gastroenteritis,
multiple causes - USA (OH)". As of 27 Aug 2004 [see: Gastroenteritis,
multiple causes - USA (OH)(06) 20040827.2396] stool samples from 19 people
were positive for the following diarrhea-causing agents: Campylobacter
(14), norovirus (3), Salmonella (1) and Giardia (1). Mod.LL commented that
the number of etiology-identified cases remains low, and most are still
Campylobacter; however, the short-lived nature of the illness speaks
against this as a major pathogen and may reflect cultures being done
because of more severe illness. As reported numbers of illnesses continue
to increase, it is still not clear whether the rise is due to more
illnesses occurring or more complete reporting.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[At the moment the identity of the etiologic agent is unresolved, and
viruses may not be the major source of infection. Further developments will
be posted in the "Gastroenteritis, multiple causes - USA (OH)" thread. -
Mod.CP]
